## 6. PHP Production Mapping (for the proposal)

The client requires PHP. The demo runs on Flask + Vanilla JS for rapid prototyping. The cover
letter must include a concrete mapping:

| Demo layer          | PHP/Laravel production equivalent    |
|---------------------|--------------------------------------|
| Flask blueprint     | Laravel Controller + Routes (web.php)|
| SQLite tables       | MySQL/PostgreSQL with Eloquent ORM   |
| PyJWT tokens        | Laravel Sanctum or Passport          |
| Vanilla JS frontend | Vue.js, Livewire, or keep vanilla JS |
| 4s client polling   | Laravel Echo + Pusher WebSockets     |
| Static file serving | Laravel on shared hosting or a VPS   |

All user flows, data models, and UI components remain identical. Only the runtime changes.
Estimated PHP/Laravel migration from this prototype: 1-2 weeks for a mid-level developer.

---

## 7. Industry Context for the Proposal

### EdTech market talking points
- School-parent communication is the #1 pain point cited in U.S. K-12 EdTech surveys
  (teachers spend an average of 30 min/day on parent communication via phone or email)
- Apps like ClassDojo have 51M users in 180 countries, proving the model scales
- Real-time grade visibility reduces parent anxiety and improves student accountability
- The MVP approach (one student, two roles, three core features) is how all major EdTech
  platforms started -- ClassDojo launched as a behavior tracker before expanding to messaging
- PHP is the dominant backend language in school district IT (many districts run on
  Laravel-based SIS integrations)

### Proposal angle for Michael
- "I built the portal live -- you can log in as parent or teacher right now"
- Emphasize the dual-role demo flow (reviewers can experience both sides in under 2 minutes)
- Highlight that real-time polling with 4s intervals is production-viable and upgrades to
  WebSockets (Laravel Echo) for the PHP version
- The PHP mapping table shows this is not a throwaway prototype -- it is a PHP-ready spec

